a matter of "saving the woman from sin," not saving the baby's life. Some view abortion as compensating for an accidental pregnancy: "It's like paying a loan - the girl comes back to you" [Gbagbo, cited in Mancini-Griffoli, Ezzati et al, 2003, p. 746].

A recent study of Mauritanian Catholic attitudes [Jaunissain & Assaye, 2007] largely confirms these data, but also reveals some important discrepancies likely reflecting the historical nature of the populations' encounters with more progressive catholic sexual morality and judaism: "In Mauritania [as in Burkina Faso], the predominance of a conservative approach to the question of abortion [54%] coexists with a 28% share of those who defend its legalization [...] For Mauritanian believers, as for believers in the Maghreb and sub-Saharan Africa more generally, abortion is usually considered as a personal fault; but, if it is performed by a doctor or other healthcare professional, it often involves a certain degree of approval. March of 27-June 1, 2007, supported 54.2% of those interviewed who saw in abortion nothing but an personal fault."
